Shares of the following companies
had unusual price changes in Philippine trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses, and prices are as of the noon close.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 0.6 percent to
3,896.31, the lowest level since March 7.    Ayala Corp. (AC)  , a the owner of the Philippinesâ€™
largest lender, rose 0.3 percent to 355 pesos, its highest close
since Feb. 4. The company said it plans to sell as much as 10
billion pesos of 10-year bonds, with a  put option  on the fifth
and the eighth year.        Nickel Asia Corp. (NIKL)   fell 4.4 percent to 19.60
pesos, its lowest close since Jan. 31. Pacific Metals Co. Ltd.
of  Japan , a shareholder and a client, stopped operations at its
Hachinoche plant due to damages caused by the earthquake.    San Miguel Corp. (SMC)  , the largest Philippine food and
drinks company, dropped 0.1 percent to 160.2 pesos, after
slumping as much as 3.5 percent earlier. Net income last year
fell to 20.1 billion pesos ($458 million) from 57.8 billion
pesos in 2009.  To contact the reporter on this story:
